The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: 1) Extracted preference/dislike from my self-introduction: I only stated that I "enjoy listening to CDs very much." There is no stated genre preference or explicit dislikes in that sentence.
2) Basis for choice (using common-knowledge, objective factors since no genre preference was given): as a CD listener wanting to get the most from the format, two useful criteria are (a) how well a release showcases the strengths of the CD medium (cleanly produced studio recordings, dynamic clarity, and variety across tracks) and (b) broad accessibility/popularity for repeated listening. "Revolutions: The Very Best Of Steve Winwood" is a curated compilation of Steve Winwood’s best-known studio recordings (e.g., "Higher Love," "Back in the High Life Again," "Valerie"—well-produced pop/rock tracks). Studio compilations like this tend to offer consistent, polished production and a variety of material across different phases of an artist’s career, which plays to the strengths of CD fidelity and makes for enjoyable, repeatable listening. By contrast, "Tokyo Tapes" is a classic rock/AOR live album (famously a Scorpions live release); live records capture concert energy and raw performance, but they typically include audience noise, performance variations, and a narrower stylistic focus (hard/classic rock), which can be less uniformly polished and less broadly accessible to a general CD listener looking for a varied, high-fidelity listening experience.
3) Specific reasons for choosing Revolutions and rejecting Tokyo Tapes:
- Chosen (Revolutions): This compilation gives a broad, polished survey of Steve Winwood’s best studio work. Studio-produced hits normally benefit from careful mixing/mastering, which highlights instrument separation, vocal detail, and dynamic range on CD—qualities a CD enthusiast appreciates. The track selection provides variety (different tempos, arrangements and eras), making it a strong choice for someone who simply enjoys listening to CDs and wants a satisfying listening session without needing a specific affinity for a harder rock live sound.
- Rejected (Tokyo Tapes): Although historically significant and appealing to classic rock/AOR fans for its live energy and authentic performance, it is a live-only experience with the characteristics of concert recordings (crowd ambience, on-the-night variations, heavier rock emphasis). Because my stated preference is only a general enjoyment of CDs (not a declared desire for live recordings or hard rock specifically), the live, genre-specific nature of Tokyo Tapes makes it a less suitable pick for a general CD-listening session focused on fidelity, variety, and broadly appealing production.
In short: given only the general enjoyment of CDs, the studio-polished, varied, and widely accessible compilation "Revolutions: The Very Best Of Steve Winwood" better aligns with maximizing the typical CD listening experience than the narrower, live-oriented "Tokyo Tapes."

