2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those points
- Candidate 2 (late‑70s/early‑80s AOR classic) is described as having uniform glossy hard‑rock production, tight, hook‑driven arrangements, punchy mixes and big singalong choruses, with concise songcraft and sequencing that rewards start‑to‑finish listening. Those traits map directly to my core likes: guitar‑forward, punchy mixes, arena‑ready gloss, layered hooks/choruses, and high replay value. There is no note about alterations that would soften dynamics or reduce guitar attack, so it reads as an original production that preserves the record’s punch.
- Candidate 1 (remastered AOR release) promises clear, balanced high‑fidelity sound, improved dynamic detail, and collector‑focused extras (liner notes, accurate track info, cohesive sequencing). Those positives align with my appreciation for production detail and good packaging. However, the description also says the remaster “tames late‑’80s gloss.” That phrase implies the remaster changes the original sheen of the era’s big productions. Because I explicitly dislike remixes/remasters that dull guitar attack or strip original punch, any remaster that alters the era’s glossy, arena‑ready character is a risk for me—even if it improves fidelity or adds liner notes.
3) Why I chose Candidate 2 and rejected Candidate 1
- Chosen: Candidate 2 best preserves the specific sonic attributes I prioritize: glossy hard‑rock production, punchy mixes, multi‑layered hooks and big singalong choruses. Its description implies the original arena‑style energy and mid‑forward guitar presence are intact, which matches my desire for albums that hit hard on CD and reveal studio craft without losing punch. The emphasis on concise, tight arrangements and consistent sequencing also aligns with my preference for records that reward start‑to‑finish listening on a good system.
