2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those points
- Blue Moves remaster:
  - Matches some technical preferences: preserved micro‑dynamics, generous headroom, non‑loudness mastering — all positives that align with my dislike of heavy limiting and my desire for headroom and transient life.
  - But its tonal and arrangement emphases conflict with core preferences: it’s tactile/close‑miked piano‑forward with an intimate, off‑center lead vocal in lush harmonies and “restrained guitars/drums.” My stated preference is for centre‑front, massive stacked vocal harmonies and multitracked crunchy guitars with punchy drums and riff‑driven arrangements. The intimate off‑centre vocal and piano focus mean the soundstage and arrangement are more chambered and personality‑driven than arena/harmony‑first AOR. While its warm analogue tone and preserved snap are good, the restraint on guitars/drums and the off‑centre vocal positioning make it a poorer match for my arena/harmony/riff priorities.
- Glossy late‑70s/early‑80s anthems:
  - Directly matches many of my core preferences: tight 3–4‑minute riff‑driven songs (within my preferred 3–5 minute singalong range), multitracked guitars, massive stacked center‑front vocal harmonies, tape‑like transient punch, analogue midrange warmth, low compression, roomy yet focused imaging, and minimal artificial reverb. That combination is essentially a checklist match for my stated tastes — vocal‑forward arena sheen, clear separation, preserved transient attack, and harmony‑first arrangements. The description also specifies restrained low end and minimal artificial reverb, which supports punchy drums and clear separation without the over‑smooth, over‑compressed mastering I dislike.
3) Choice and why I reject the other
- I choose the glossy late‑70s/early‑80s anthems because it aligns with the central elements I value most: center‑front, massive stacked vocal harmonies and multitracked, riff‑driven guitar arrangements with preserved transient attack and low compression. Its tape‑like transient punch, analogue midrange warmth applied in a restrained way, roomy focused imaging and minimal reverb all support the arena, harmony‑first AOR sound I specifically favor. The songs’ 3–4‑minute lengths are exactly the riff‑driven, singalong format I look for, and the production notes indicate careful mastering rather than heavy limiting — addressing my dislike of over‑compressed, brick‑wall mastering that kills micro‑dynamics.
- I reject the Blue Moves remaster because, although it ticks some technical boxes (non‑loudness mastering, preserved dynamics, analogue tone), its intimate, piano‑led presentation and off‑center lead vocal in lush, restrained arrangements run counter to my preference for center‑front, massive stacked harmonies and crunching multitracked guitars with punchy drums. The emphasis on close‑miked piano and restrained guitars/drums means the record leans toward an intimate listening experience rather than the glossy, arena‑scale, harmony‑heavy AOR sound I prioritize. In short: Blue Moves gets credit for tasteful mastering and dynamics, but it doesn’t deliver the multitracked, riff‑driven, center‑front vocal sheen and punch I want, whereas the glossy late‑70s/early‑80s anthems do.

