The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: 1) Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self‑introduction)
- Preferences: midrange‑forward, tape‑tinged arena AOR sound; massive, multitracked crunchy guitars and huge stacked vocal harmonies up front; preserved transient guitar attack; punchy gated/snappy drums; tight focused bass; uncut full‑length solos presented in roomy stereo; restrained tape saturation, generous headroom, minimal multiband limiting; careful mastering that preserves micro‑dynamics and percussive snap while still delivering a glossy arena sheen for 3–5 minute riff‑driven singalongs; clear separation between parts and vocal‑forward clarity when supported by strong backing stacks; low compression to preserve punch.
- Dislikes: groove‑first pop‑soul presentations with intimate single‑lead vocals and sparse harmonies; excessive tube warmth or warm/elastic low end that blurs transients; over‑smooth or heavily limited mastering; thin/mono imaging; mixes that downplay stacked harmonies or full‑length solos.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those criteria
- Performance‑first 'Faith': Described as having a center‑front warm 1970s midrange lead, lush multitracked harmonies, wide coherent imaging and palpable melodic solos. The warm analogue remaster explicitly preserves transient snap, microdynamics and generous headroom, with tasteful (i.e., restrained) compression, punchy rhythms and forward guitars. That ticks the majority of my boxes: midrange focus, tape/analogue sheen, strong multitracked harmonies up front, roomy/wide imaging, preserved transients and microdynamics, tasteful compression and notable melodic solos.
- Back in Black: Described as attack‑first, riff‑driven with midrange‑forward, tactile guitar bite, locked punchy bass/drums, tight low end, fast transient attack, minimal compression and warm analogue sheen. Vocals are singer‑forward and “sit with the groove,” and the presentation emphasizes locked rhythm and attack. This aligns with my desire for preserved transients, minimal compression and punchy rhythm, and riff focus. However, it emphasizes a groove‑anchored, singer‑forward delivery and tight low‑end lock rather than lush multitracked, arena‑fronted harmonies and roomy solo presentation.
3) Why I choose 'Faith' and reject 'Back in Black'
- Chosen: Performance‑first 'Faith' best matches the combination of my priorities. The explicit presence of lush multitracked harmonies up front is a primary deciding factor: I value huge stacked vocal harmonies and vocal‑forward clarity when they are supported by backing stacks, and Faith calls this out directly. Its wide coherent imaging and palpable melodic solos satisfy my preference for roomy stereo presentation and uncut, prominent solos. The analogue remaster preserving transient snap, microdynamics and generous headroom with tasteful compression aligns exactly with my requirement for restrained tape saturation and minimal limiting to keep percussive snap and micro‑dynamics intact while still providing an arena sheen. Forward guitars and punchy rhythms with hook‑forward sequencing also match my desire for 3–5 minute riff‑driven singalongs that remain guitar‑centric and punchy without excessive smoothing or compression.
- Rejected: Back in Black, while excellent on many of my technical criteria (midrange‑forward guitar bite, fast transient attack, tight/punchy bass and drums, minimal compression and preserved headroom), emphasizes an attack‑first, groove‑locked presentation with singer‑forward vocals that “sit with the groove.” That runs counter to two of my core dislikes: groove‑first single‑lead vocal presentations with sparse harmonies, and mixes that downplay stacked harmonies or roomy solo space. Back in Black’s tight low‑end and locked rhythm section suggest a less spacious, more rhythm‑centric mix than I prefer for arena AOR with multitracked vocal stacks and long solo passages. In short, Back in Black sacrifices the multilayered vocal fronting, wide imaging and roomy solo space that are central to my listening priorities, even though it nails attack and punch.
Therefore, because Faith delivers the midrange‑forward, tape‑tinged arena sheen with prominent multitracked harmonies, preserved transients, generous headroom, tasteful analogue mastering and roomy solo/imaging characteristics I prioritize, it is the better match for my tastes than the groove‑anchored, singer‑forward Back in Black.

