The user updates his self-description as follows: I now prefer live, midrange‑forward arena AOR — massively multitracked crunchy guitars and colossal stacked live harmonies with a gritty lead up front; tape‑like transient punch, roomy stereo and generous headroom. I favor tight gated drums, snapping focused bass and uncut 3–5‑minute solos that preserve percussive snap. Mastering should use restrained tape saturation, minimal limiting, and enough headroom to keep micro‑dynamics and transient attack.
From my earlier tastes I retain a love of clear separation between parts, vocal‑forward clarity when supported by strong backing stacks, and a glossy arena sheen that doesn’t smear transients. I value low compression to preserve punch and focused midrange presence.
I dislike groove‑first pop‑soul with intimate single‑lead vocals and sparse harmonies, excessive tube warmth or elastic low end that blurs transients, over‑smooth or heavily limited masters, thin/mono imaging, and mixes that truncate or downplay full‑length solos.

