  - Mastering: description implies a glossy arena sheen but preserved dynamics rather than heavy limiting, which is what I value.
  - Potential unknown: it doesn’t explicitly say “full‑length uncut solos,” but the late‑70s/early‑80s arena anthem context and “tight riffs” make it far more likely to include riff‑driven solos than an acoustic anthology would.
- Candidate 1 (Bright, acoustic‑forward anthology):
  - Acoustic/close intimacy: “bright, acoustic‑forward” and “close three‑part harmonies, minimal overdubs” point to an intimate, pocketed, melody‑first presentation — the opposite of the arena, multitracked, harmony‑first sound I prioritize.
  - Minimal overdubs and no glossy sheen: while preserved microdynamics, natural ambience and restrained processing are positives relative to my dislike of over‑limiting, the anthology explicitly lacks “glossy sheen,” and its minimal overdubs conflict with my desire for massive stacked harmonies and multitracked guitars.
  - Vocal presentation: “tightly blended, human‑in‑the‑room vocals” and “no glossy sheen” veer into the intimate, single‑lead or sparsely stacked territory I dislike (I prefer large, center‑front stacked harmonies and a more arenaized front end).
